THE WASHINGTON POST

Video clips of the live stream posted as late as 11 p.m. showed an empty street — suggesting the vehicles had moved into the area before the flames.

For about an hour after 1:30 a.m., more vehicles arrived, some outside the view of the camera, and headed toward the plant. The view then panned right to show that a white building — a training center, according to Google Maps — appeared to have caught fire, with a bright blaze obscuring the entrance.

Shortly afterward, multiple munitions could be seen being fired across the screen. Two blasts appeared to make contact — the latter striking the top of the building nearest to the camera.

Several hours later, there was still activity on the scene. At 3:30 a.m., figures were seen moving in between the military vehicles, and other vehicles appeared to be driving up to the facility. Later, a crowd of people emerged, appearing to move away from the plant even as others headed toward it.
