In Russian-allied Venezuela, protesters support Ukraine
Return to menu
By María Paúl 8:30 p.m.
Link copied
Link

    #AHORA | Sociedad civil y dirigentes políticos de la oposición en #Venezuela protestaron frente a la sede de la Unión Europea, en Caracas, para rechazar la invasión de #Rusia a #Ucrania . #3Mar pic.twitter.com/TrnrBVMXHa
    — VPItv (@VPITV) March 3, 2022 

Scores of Venezuelans on Thursday protested Russia’s invasion of Ukraine, in what appears to be the first demonstration in a Russian-allied nation.

Carrying sunflowers, posters and Venezuelan and Ukrainian flags, the demonstrators screamed “Putin, you’re an assassin” and “no to the invasion,” videos shared across social media show, as they gathered in front of the European Union’s representative headquarters in Caracas.

Their message of solidarity to Ukraine was a stark contrast to the support their country has pledged to Russia — a nation that has purchased Venezuela’s oil exports and provided it with foreign aid, arms sales and loans .

    #3Mar #Caracas #Guerra #Ucrania #Rusia @joserckeller : #Venezuela apoya a Ucrania. Manifestación en la embajada de la Unión Europea en Caracas contra la invasión no provocada de Putin a Ucrania. pic.twitter.com/7PixXDRZpB
    — Reporte Ya (@ReporteYa) March 3, 2022 

Venezuelan President Nicolás Maduro said he spoke on the phone Tuesday with Russian President Vladimir Putin — tweeting a photo of the two shaking hands in a message blaming Ukraine’s conflict on “the destabilizing actions of NATO.” Maduro has also affirmed Venezuela would provide any military or financial support Russia requires.

But Thursday’s protest brought back parallels from 2014 — a year marked by increased solidarity between Ukrainian and Venezuelan opposition groups as they both attempted to topple their authoritarian governments .

“We will always remember how in 2014, while thousands of Venezuelans were in the streets defending democracy, our flag was raised in the streets of Ukraine in the middle of Maidan Square,” said opposition leader Juan Guaidó, who is recognized as Venezuela’s president by the United States and dozens of other nations.

    Desde Venezuela nos solidarizamos con el pueblo de Ucrania y nos unimos a su lucha por la libertad,el respeto a los derechos civiles y a su soberanía. El respaldo de la dictadura a las intenciones intervencionistas de Rusia no nos representan y también ponen en riesgo a la región pic.twitter.com/abUpyeVAEm
    — Luis Somaza (@LuisSomaza) February 23, 2022 

During Thursday’s protest Guaidó said his government had assembled a volunteer mission to provide medical help in Ukraine’s borders. So far, he said, the group counts with 11 people who emigrated from Venezuela.

"Although it’s a modest contribution, from a country that is under a dictatorship, for us it’s deeply significant given our situation,” Guaidó said.
